<TEXT>
the new george bush looks sounds and acts a 
lot like the old one but he stands alone now with a scant three 
months to prove himself a leader who deserves the kind of loyalty 
he has been delivering 
his hour upon the stage at the republican national convention 
was a solid sendoff for the campaign against democratic 
presidential nominee michael dukakis even though bush imagemakers 
oversold the performance they had said it was going to a sort of 
debut an introduction to the american electorate 
bush himself said it was the most important speech of his 
career an unmatched opportunity to present himself and his goals 
but this was no transformation indeed if one were needed the 
vice president selfdescribed underdog to dukakis would be in far 
worse campaign trouble 
he needed no introduction he needed to blend the promise of 
continuity with a set of goals to call his own that is the task 
and the dilemma that makes running for president as vice president 
a daunting assignment 
bush also had to get his convention back on its script after a 
day of controversy over the military record of sen dan quayle of 
indiana his vice presidential nominee 
that issue remains a problem for quayle and therefore for bush 
but it barely intruded on the gop finale quayle was nominated 
without so much as a murmur of dissent and drew no louder cheers 
than when he said he was proud of his stint in the national guard 
the service that kept him out of the vietnam draft 
it was a distraction bush didnt need on a night he and his 
strategists considered crucial had bush stuck to his plan to name 
his running mate on thursday instead of moving it up two days he 
would have avoided the quayle flap questions about his military 
record and about stringpulling to get into the national guard 
surely would have arisen but they wouldnt have emerged in the 
hothouse atmosphere of a political convention where such things 
flourish 
nevertheless bush accomplished what he set out to do he said 
his piece with humor and style he played the cheering crowd 
effectively sometimes speaking over the din sometimes pausing to 
take the ovations 
neither dukakis nor bush ranks among the masters of political 
oratory both dukakis and bush rose to their occasions the 
democratic nominee in his atlanta acceptance speech and bush in his 
thursday night address 
bush said it was the night his campaign really began he spoke 
of the achievements of the reagan administration and claimed a 
