<DOCNO> AP880819-0054 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in 1939 arnold childs had everything a 
21yearold could ask for his health good friends an ivy league 
college degree and a promising job at nbc in new york city 
but the idealistic youth gave it up to cut wood dig potatoes 
and do maintenance on a vermont farm part of an depressionera 
experiment in communal living intended to show that citizenship 
means community service 
the camp in the tiny town of tunbridge population 200 at the 
time soon became a darling of eleanor roosevelt and the focus of 
nationwide media attention but it was closed after only three 
years when world war ii claimed many of the men who volunteered 
on thursday some of the work crew were reunited as dozens of 
people came to tunbridge to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the 
birth of eugen rosenstockhuessy a dartmouth college professor who 
helped found camp william james and others like it in the 1930s he 
died in 1973 
rosenstockhuessys idea was to develop a service program in 
which young adults from across the country would live together and 
perform chores that would benefit the community 
the idea was to actually make some changes in the civilian 
conservation corps the new deal program established in 1933 to 
give jobs to unemployed youths said jack preiss who helped found 
the camp and wrote a book about it 
what we were trying to do is make the corps the work service 
a more democratic opportunity because it was confined to unemployed 
kids from the cities he said and we felt public service is 
something everyone should do from college students to youths in 
the slums to young adults in tunbridge 
the camp was founded on philosopher william james theory that 
work service is the moral equivalent of war that uniting 
people from all walks of life could foster peace camaraderie and 
the spirit of community 
we could never really have war if people are working face to 
face said rosenstockhuessys granddaughter margaret huessy 
i dont think anyone could actually kill anyone if they knew 
them 
childs 69 a columbus ohio native who now lives in eugene 
ore left his new york job when he heard about the camp from 
fellow dartmouth graduates i was getting a little tired of the 
city and i thought the project would be an adventure he said 
at first he and other participants lived in barracks at a ccc 
camp in the nearby central vermont town of sharon they harvested 
crops worked on machinery and cleared fire lanes 
i was milking 15 holsteins twice a day said preiss 68 now 
a sociology professor at duke university in durham nc 
to develop the experiment they solicited government funds and 
tried to gain community support by assisting residents with farm 
and other tasks 
the camp which moved to tunbridge when the workers acquired a 
farm was visited by mrs roosevelt in 1941 
it also caught the eye of journalist and poet dorothy thompson 
who presented president franklin roosevelt with citizen petitions 
asking him to support the camp she collected the papers in the 
tunbridge town hall basement where former campers and other 
students of rosenstockhuessy gathered for lunch thursday 
preiss and others said the spirit of the camp remained when it 
folded in 1942 and they returned to mainstream society the camp 
was cited when the peace corps was established in 1961 preiss said 
childs spent 1970 to 1980 overseas working for the united 
nations world food program i found that particularly working in 
countries like india and nepal the work i did on the farms and 
camp william james i can definitely see the connection between 
development work and work at the camp 
after lunch the former campers went outside to perform one last 
community service project they fanned out in tunbridges 
cemeteries to map veterans gravestones for memorial day ceremonies 
next year 
citizenship means giving something back to the community 
preiss said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
