<TEXT>
maung maung an americaneducated 
intellectual and burmas first civilian leader in 26 years is seen 
as a figurehead for military powerbrokers but a leader who could 
calm violent antigovernment protests 
maung maung recently named the countrys attorneygeneral 
today was elected chairman of the ruling political party burmas 
most powerful post and the countrys president 
although maung maung has been closely associated with the 
military dominated political system that activists seek to 
dismantle some analysts say his civilian status and only indirect 
involvement in the recent ruthless suppression of dissent may serve 
to blunt the protest movement 
the 63yearold maung maung has been a journalist lawyer and 
author who joined senior government and party ranks following the 
1962 coup by ne win 
he is described by tzang yawnghwe an author and son of burmas 
first president as one of the few burmese intellectuals who 
sincerely and deeply admired gen ne win 
maung maung served as ne wins personal legal adviser wrote a 
flattering book burma and general ne win about the 
authoritarian leader and was one of the architects of the 
countrys 1974 constitution 
he was born jan 11 1925 and graduated from high school in 
mandalay the former royal capital he enrolled at mandalay 
universitys law school but his higher education was interrupted by 
the outbreak of world war ii and the fight for burmese independence 
from great britain 
maung maung joined the burma independence army a ragtag but 
fiery outfit organized by the leaders of the independence struggle 
known as the thirty comrades the army which included ne win 
in a key leadership role marched into burma from thailand in early 
1942 initially bent on fighting with the japanese against the 
british but later switching to the allied side 
rising from a private to second lieutentant maung maung wrote 
romantically of his army days in a 1974 autobiographical work 
called to a soldier son 
the army has remained my second home in all my wanderings over 
the years maung maung wrote in a passage reflecting his intimate 
relationship with burmas military rulers 
after burma gained independence in 1948 maung maung studied at 
rangoon university describing himself as an eternal student 
maung maung later received a doctorate in international law from 
utrecht university in the netherlands and a law degree from yale 
university where he spent two years as a visiting lecturer in the 
early 1960s 
following the 1962 coup he served as chief justice and in 1971 
became a member of the ruling revolutionary council he was also 
elected to the central committee of the burma socialist program 
party 
after the promulgation of the 1974 constitution which he helped 
write and the replacement of the council by a formal government 
apparatus maung maung became a member of the powerful council of 
state 
the constitution formalized ne wins burmese way to 
socialism an amalgam of socialism buddhist philosophy and 
centralized oneparty rule in its international relations burma 
took a strictly nonaligned stance 
maung maung was elected to the partys central executive 
committee at the third party congress in 1976 and was ranked fifth 
in the party hierarchy he resigned from this committee at the 
fifth congress in 1985 
following the resignation of ne win as chairman july 23 his 
replacement by sein lwin and the subsequent shakeups in both 
party and government ranks maung maung returned to the central 
executive committee 
he was also named attorneygeneral making him only one of two 
civilians among retired or active military officers in the top 
echelons of government the other is education minister kyaw sein 
hugh c macdougall a burma scholar and former us diplomat in 
rangoon said thursday that maung maung had a higher profile abroad 
than inside burma most burmese macdougall said realized a man 
like maung maung was of limited consequence yet from the outside he 
was seen as a unique species a rare civilian among military 
powerbrokers 
i dont see him as anyone likely to take over the real 
leadership macdougall said in an interview 
american burma scholar josef silverstein and several other burma 
experts contacted said they expect a transitional government that 
would try to calm political turbulence and institute some economic 
reforms 
silverstein said that whoever emerged as formal leader would 
probably be controlled by military figures 
but even as a mouthpiece maung maungs ability to deal with the 
current crisis and his appeal among student activists would be 
important 
youth is the time of ideals of anger of energy he wrote 
in the 1974 book how to turn those ideals anger and energy to 
happy and creative purposes is the challenge that society must meet 
all the time 
 
</TEXT>
