iraqs proposed purchase of an idle texas 
steel plant from usx corp appears to raise no national security 
questions a commerce department official said friday 
the technology is very old very outmoded said the 
official adding that department officials dont anticipate any 
national security issues to be involved 
the official spoke on condition he not be identified 
a justice department spokesman mark sheehan said the 
department was taking a preliminary look at whether the proposed 
sale warranted an antitrust investigation 
rep jack fields rtexas who strongly opposes the deal said 
iraqs ambassador to the united states abdulamir alanbari had 
told him a 1 million downpayment already had been made to usx a 
pittsburghbased steel and energy concern 
fields represents a district near houston that includes the 
baytown steel plant he has asked president reagan the justice 
department the pentagon and the commerce department to investigate 
the proposed sale on grounds that it poses national security risks 
and that it would unlawfully limit domestic competition 
i am convinced usx is trying to keep the price of steel slab 
and steel plate high fields said 
william p ryder a usx spokesman confirmed that negotiations 
to sell the steel plant to iraq were under way but he would not 
comment on a new york times report that iraq was willing to pay 
100 million for the 20yearold equipment 
the times report said iraq had indicated it wanted the 
steelmaking equipment to help expand production in its oil fields 
which are linked to an extensive network of pipelines 
efforts to reach officials at the iraqi embassy in washington on 
friday were unsuccessful 
fields claimed two us companies were ready to pay a price 
comparable to the iraqi offer he identified them as major 
financial services corp of tallahassee fla and birmingham steel 
corp of birmingham ala 
fields said usx had made statements that have led me to 
believe they really do not want to sell to an american company 
they want to remove capacity it keeps their prices high 
ryder said the company would not respond to fields claims 
fields said he was concerned that usx would be exporting state 
of the art armorizing technology which is used for tanks and other 
military applications 
at the pentagon spokesman lt col keith schneider said on 
the surface it is not a defense issue 
the plant which once employed as many as 2000 people was shut 
down two years ago amid labor turmoil and declining demand for 
steel it had produced up to 13 million tons a year of 
largediameter pipe used for us oil and natural gas pipelines 
the works includes electric furnaces for melting scrap casters 
to shape molten steel into slabs and a mill for making slabs into 
oil drilling pipe 
fields said 750 people could be employed if the plant were 
reopened 
