newspaper was based on interviews with 1021 britons this month 
the church of england has an allmale priesthood in the last 11 
years a minority of the 26 selfgoverning anglican churches in 
other countries including the 25million member us episcopal 
church have ordained more than 1000 women as priests the us 
church and those in canada and new zealand are considering 
consecrating the first women bishops this year 
results of the gallup survey contrasted with a close vote on the 
womens role issue at the churchs general synod on july 5 
the synod voted 299216 to draft legislation allowing ordination 
of women the breakdown of votes was bishops 2821 clergy 137102 
and laity 13493 with one abstention 
the draft legislation must be debated and voted upon by all 44 
of the state churchs dioceses it will then go back to the synod 
for final approval and must then be passed by parliament to become 
law the first woman could be ordained in 1992 or 1993 
asked if they thought the church of england should accept women 
as priests and bishops 70 percent of the britons polled agreed 
that it should 18 percent disagreed and 12 percent were undecided 
the group included anglicans people of other faiths and 
nonchurch goers the response to the same question among only 
anglicans in the 1021 people surveyed was 75 percent agreeing 16 
percent disagreeing and nine percent undecided 
the paper did not indicate how many of the 1021 were anglicans 
and gave no margin of error 
