<TEXT>
a federal appeals court ruled friday that the 
reagan administration had not justified its failure to replace with 
new examinations a civil service test that was found to 
discriminate against minorities 
the us circuit court of appeals here said the office of 
personnel management acted arbitrarily and capriciously when 
did not provide figures to document its claim it would be too 
costly to devise new tests 
but the threejudge panel said opm should be given another 
opportunity to justify the decision to the judge who ordered the 
agency to devise new tests for college graduates seeking 
entrylevel federal jobs 
the decision came in a case brought by the national treasury 
employees union that challenged opms decision to hire employees 
for entrylevel positions under a noncompetitive provision of the 
civil service law 
that provision gives government agencies discretion to hire 
employees noncompetitively 
the employees union objected to the procedure because the 
employees hired under the provision did not receive all the 
protections afforded other civilservice workers 
the dispute arose after the goverment signed a consent decree in 
1982 to phase out the professional and administrative career 
examination to settle a lawsuit claiming the test discriminated 
unfairly against minorities 
us district judge joyce hens green ordered opm to devise new 
examinations to cover specific jobs and to implement the new tests 
in six months she stayed her order to give the government an 
opportunity to appeal the decision 
the appeals court in an opinion by circuit judge douglas h 
ginsburg sided with greens finding that she had jurisdiction to 
examine opms decision and with the conclusion it was arbitrarily 
and capricious 
opm did not have any evidence so far as the record reveals 
of how much it would cost to develop the necessary examinations 
ginsburg wrote in an opinion joined by circuit judges patricia wald 
and harry edwards 
unable to point us to any data of the sort it would have 
considered if it had considered cost in any meaningful way opm 
urges us to defer to its expert judgment regarding the cost of 
developing new examinations 
there is no indication in the record however that opm ever 
made an expert judgment about what those costs would be ginsburg 
wrote 
opm spokesman dick mcgowan said the agency would not comment on 
the decision 
in june opm administrator constance horner announced a new 
program of using campus recruiters to hire college graduates based 
on their academic records and interviews horner said the agency 
would also devise competitive examinations for students who did not 
have high enough grades to be hired through interviews 
the treasury employees union has filed a new suit to challenge 
the proposal contending it will not result in competitive hiring 
the unions president robert tobias said fridays decision 
means that opm can no longer ignore their obligation to develop 
an alternative system 
