<TEXT>
amendments to the constitution went into 
effect friday giving president daniel arap moi greater control 
over the judiciary and broadening the arrest powers of the police 
the amendments were printed friday in a supplement to the kenya 
gazette 
parliament voted unanimously aug 2 to amend the constitution to 
empower the president to fire a high court judge or court of 
appeals judge without reason and without having to go through a 
tribunal process 
it gave the head of state the same power to fire members of the 
public service commission 
parliament also changed the constitution to allow police to hold 
a capital crime suspect for 14 days instead of the previous 24 
hours before bringing him to court 
traditionally there is a 14day waiting period between the time 
a constitutional change is proposed and debate in parliament but 
the measures sailed through the chamber unopposed five days after 
the attorney general proposed them 
lawyers and clergymen fought the changes saying they would 
erode the checks and balances between the executive and the 
judiciary and undermine individual liberties 
kenya by law is a oneparty state and approval of the 
constitutional changes had been expected 
