<TEXT>
a federal appeals court friday supported 
a judges order imposing a property tax increase to finance kansas 
city school desegregation but said the judge overstepped his 
authority when he imposed an income tax surcharge 
gov john ashcroft criticized the 8th us circuit court of 
appeals ruling saying it is one more step toward the day when 
federal judges control more and more institutions in our society 
our prisons schools and social services programs 
us district judge russell g clark ordered the tax increases 
in september 1987 to pay for desegregation in the kansas city 
school district the money also was for construction of new schools 
that could lure white students from the suburbs and private schools 
many of the citys school buildings have literally rotted 
clark said about threequarters of the students are minorities 
about twothirds of them are black 
clark ordered the tax increases when no money was available to 
finance the construction of new schools and after voters in the 
district turned down six proposals to increase taxes for education 
between 1970 and 1983 
he ordered that taxes on property in the school district be 
almost doubled and that people who worked in kansas city whether 
or not they lived there pay a 15 percent state income tax 
surcharge 
missouri attorney general william webster appealed clarks 
order among those filing briefs opposing the taxes were the 
justice department the state of kansas and us sen john 
danforth rmo 
in its ruling friday the appeals court dismissed the states 
contention that clark exceeded his judicial authority in imposing 
the property tax increase 
the threemember panel in st louis said it holds that federal 
courts powers to remedy the evils of segregation include a 
narrowly defined power to order increases in local tax levies on 
real estate 
the court said it had ruled in another case that a federal court 
could impose such a tax increase only after exploration of every 
other fiscal alternative 
but noting that the property tax is the established source of 
revenue for missouris school districts the court said clark could 
not impose a state income tax surcharge because it restructures 
the states scheme of school financing and creates an entirely new 
form of taxing authority 
we are satisfied that the district court invaded the province 
of the legislature in ordering this surcharge the appellate 
court ruled adding that unspent revenues must be refunded 
the appeals court dismissed the states contention that the 
federal judge had exceeded his authority in imposing the property 
tax increase 
bobby george a spokesman for the missouri attorney generals 
office said the state would appeal all or part of the ruling or 
ask for a rehearing by the full appeals court 
kansas gov mike hayden applauded the decision kansans who 
worked in kansas city mo were affected by the income tax 
surcharge 
officials of the landmark legal foundation which had been a 
party in an appeal of the clarks order vowed to continue the 
effort to overturn the property tax increase 
clarks ruling stemmed from a 1977 lawsuit filed on behalf of 
kansas city students that sought to correct the decline of 
predominantly black urban schools the us district court found 
that the city school district had allowed vestiges of segregation 
to remain despite us supreme court orders ordering desegration 
in 1954 and 1969 
</TEXT>
