the rodent in a 16ounce can of coors on july 29 said the autopsy 
was only slighly more scientific than tealeaf reading 
coors officials released a report from university of florida 
veterinary pathologist claus buergelt who performed a 
courtordered autopsy on the mouse 
the tests performed by the university of florida clearly prove 
that the mouse did not get into the can in golden colo said 
cary baird a coors spokeswoman 
she said the examination did not disclose the cause of death but 
showed the mouse was dead approximately one week or less when the 
necropsy was conducted 
the beer was packaged on may 13 some 77 days before harvey 
reported finding the animal to coors 
but pathologist ed willey who was hired by harveys attorney 
disputed the findings on the time of the rodents death 
willey said that because the mouse had been kept in beer it 
would have decomposed more slowly than it would have at a natural 
rate 
i suggest that the only appropriate interpretation of dr 
buergelts findings is that the death of the mouse was at least one 
week prior to autopsy and possibly several days or more prior to 
the canning of the product willey said 
ms baird said experts were asked to determine if the condition 
of the mouse was consistent with one that had been in a beer can 
for that time 
the answer is a resounding no she said 
a creature that had been in a sealed can of beer since may 13 
when this can was packaged would show more evidence of 
decomposition than this sample she said 
there was a oneweek lapse from the time harvey reported his 
find to coors until the mouse was examined 
although the report indicates that the mouse was dead less 
than one week it is critical to note here that the sample was 
frozen at least twice during the week freezing greatly retards 
decompostion thus making the reported time frame consistent with 
how the sample was actually handled she said 
harvey 30 an unemployed construction worker told the media he 
found the mouse after sipping a coors beer and becoming ill he and 
a television crew took the can to the jacksonville health 
department on aug 3 officials there cut the can open and poured 
out its contents which included a dead mouse 
harveys attorney gary pajcic said that his client is out of 
state and would not be available for comment 
</TEXT>
