<TEXT>
just a few months ago britains economic 
disease of rampant inflation skyhigh interest rates and 
persistent unemployment was pronounced cured by just about everyone 
except the conservative governments staunchest critics 
today the economy is suffering something of a relapse 
exhibiting that old familiar symptom higher inflation and the 
government admits it is troubling 
in addition a hike in interest rates and a sharp widening of 
the trade deficit are worrying economists 
ironically the symptoms cause is the economys vigorous 
growth which is stretching resources and driving up prices like 
its trading ally the united states britain faces the threat that 
its economy could overheat into recession 
the peak came in march when the treasurys top official 
chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson announced the first 
surplus budget in nearly 20 years and slashed the top income tax 
rate to 40 percent from 60 percent 
since then the attention has turned instead to britains annual 
inflation rate which fed by strong consumer spending has jumped 
from 35 percent to 48 percent in july in his budget speech 
lawson had forecast an inflation rate of 4 percent by the end of 
the year 
to combat higher inflation prime minister margaret thatchers 
no 1 economic priority the government has pushed interest rates 
up more than 35 percentage points since early june 
whatever action is necessary to keep inflation under control 
this government will take lawson told members of parliament in 
late july characterizing the pickup as modest but unacceptable 
strength in the dollar gave the government room to raise 
interest rates without pushing the british pound dangerously high 
but the pound which has been trading at about 320 west german 
marks remains well above a rate of 3 marks which the government 
long had protected 
the pound broke through that ceiling in march raising concerns 
that britains export competitiveness might be hurt indeed the 
trade deficit is much worse than lawson had forecast 
for the first six months of 1988 britain had a current account 
deficit of 56 billion pounds 96 billion compared with a 16 
billion pound 26 billion deficit in all of 1987 the current 
account includes invisible trade such as services and overseas 
investment earnings 
in his budget speech lawson had forecast a trade deficit of 4 
billion pounds 7 billion for all of 1988 
things have deteriorated said ian harwood an economist at 
the london investment firm warburg securities the major part of 
the reason for the deterioration has been the way the economy has 
been growing so much faster than expected 
david owen an economist with the london investment firm 
kleinwort grieveson ltd said domestic demand is just growing 
too quickly for its own good 
the latest survey conducted by the polling organization market 
and opinion research international showed that in july for the 
first time since february 1987 more people thought the state of 
the economy would get worse rather than better over the next year 
economists expect britains gross domestic product its total 
output of goods and services to grow between 35 percent and 4 
percent this year faster than the 3 percent forecast by lawson in 
march and following growth of 44 percent in 1987 
on top of the troubling symptoms there have been recurrent 
reports of a rift between mrs thatcher and lawson over currency 
exchange policy 
these have been fueled by the pounds rise and the governments 
negotiations with mrs thatchers former economic adviser sir alan 
walters for him to return to her downing street office next year 
mrs thatcher advocates freemarket policies while lawson favors 
managing exchange rates through direct intervention in the markets 
and the adjustment of interest rates 
however lawson survived a cabinet reshuffle by mrs thatcher in 
late july and now appears likely to remain until at least after 
next springs budget 
but the economic outlook remains worrying harwood said 
inflation will peak at 6 percent early next year interest rates 
might move higher into the double digits and the trade deficit 
probably will balloon to 10 billion pounds 172 billion in 1988 
harwood predicted 
the government remains upbeat 
the difficulties that beset us are difficulties we have 
successfully dealt with in the past and will do so again without 
drama and without interrupting the steady progress we have already 
achieved lawson said 
