<TEXT>
at the end of their shift the miners 
of jastrzebie trade their cramped quarters in the coal pits for 
their tiny apartments in concrete highrises 
many miners in this town at the center of the latest wave of 
polish strikes must toil seven days a week to supplement their 
wages and gain access to special stores that are open only to 
miners who agree to work weekends 
they say long lines for food irregular family life and constant 
manipulation of their interests by management led to anger 
frustration and the strikes that began tuesday in this mountain 
town of 100000 near the czechoslovakian border 
what kind of a family life can a man have here said a miner 
in his mid30s speaking in his tworoom apartment overlooking the 
mine he asked that his name not be used 
for many miners the outlawed trade union solidarity gave them a 
voice and hope that they could change the way they work and live 
residents are still proud that key agreements between solidarity 
and the government were signed in jastrzebie in september 1980 
and they will never forget the nine miners killed by security 
police at the wujek mine near katowice about 35 miles to the 
northeast after martial law was imposed in december 1981 
