<DOCNO> AP880819-0301 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
venezuela is sticking a second toe into the 
waters of the international bond market with a new 100 million 
issue 
the 5year eurobond issue is small by the standards of todays 
capital markets but in light of the international debt crisis it 
has a symbolic value it marks only the second time that a 
developing nation debtor has ventured into the world bond market 
since the debt problem began in 1982 
since then third world debtors have raised cash mainly with big 
loans from foreign commercial banks and international organizations 
not by tapping bond investors 
the first testing of the the post1982 waters also belonged to 
venezuela last february the latin american oil producer launched 
its first international bond issue since the crisis a 100 
million issue underwritten by jp morgan securities and banco de 
venezuela a private bank 
although most of the bonds were purchased by venezuelan 
investors the issue was considered a success and emboldened the 
caracas government to try a second time 
there are several reasons why it has been the venezuelans 
rather than other third world debtors who have ventured into the 
market although it too has its problems the venezuelan economy 
with the help of oil revenues is considered more stable than 
those of most other debtor nations the country has paid back a big 
portion of its foreign debt which now stands at around 34 billion 
experts say the new bonds to be issued on monday are really a 
way for the venezuelans to measure the countrys creditworthiness 
in the eyes of foreign investors by nurturing the perception that 
venezuela is again welcome in the capital markets the venezuelans 
could become less dependent on foreign banks the international 
monetary fund and the world bank 
theyre in a kind of quasimarket borrowing status said 
robert mccauley an economist for the joint economic committee of 
congress 
loans from the imf and the world bank are politically sensitive 
since they carry strings often in the form of required economic 
austerity programs in the borrowing countries 
the sensitivity has been heightened in venezuela by the 
presidential election scheduled for early december since the debt 
issue can provide powerful ammunition for the opposition parties 
although carlos andres perez a candidate from the ruling accion 
democratica party is widely expected to win it is not clear 
whether he will continue the governments current debt policies 
even the organizers of the new bond issue acknowledge the 
prickliness of the situation oliver parr a director of samuel 
montagu amp co ltd in london conceded the upcoming election makes 
the timing of the issue not entirely satisfactory 
the foreign debt issue is a highly political matter in all 
latin american countries parr said 
the new bonds will be offered to investors on a highrisk 
highyield basis not unlike the junk bonds that have gained 
popularity in this country as a way to finance corporate takeovers 
the venezuelan bonds carry a yield of 1875 percentage point 
over the london interbank offered rate known as the libor rate a 
widely used benchmark for international issues 
its pretty much a junk spread over libor mccauley said 
other sovereign bonds from triplea borrowers such as 
britain have been offered at the libor rate while south korea 
recently offered bonds at only a quarter point over the benchmark 
rate 
still everythings relative and the venezuelan bonds appear to 
have a better chance than other debtors bonds would 
venezuela is deemed to be in better shape a new york banker 
said its a working political system that can deal with change 
</TEXT>
